column168: Description Of Events

A Memphis spill agent was called to the dangerous goods building for a leaking class 3 package. The agent was presented a fiberboard box that had signs of a release on the bottom edge of the fiberboard box. While investigating the package it was discovered that one of the four plastic bottles inside had a loose cap.  The cap was tightened, and all contents were placed into a steel salvage package. The shipper will be contacted for an amended shipper's declaration for movement.

column25: A&F TRADING / A DC TO STORE
column168: The Memphis spill office was presented a fiberboard box containing a class 9 with signs of release. The fiberboard box contained eight smaller boxes of cologne. One of the eight bottles was broken releasing its contents inside of the fiberboard box the other seven bottles were intact. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and a new shippers declaration will be obtained before movement.

A Memphis spill agent was called to the dangerous goods building for a fiberboard box containing a class 3 have appeared to be leaking. While investigating the fiberboard box the agent found two glass bottles inside and one of them was broken releasing its contents inside of the box. The bottles were in plastic bags with bubble wrap and surrounded by Styrofoam. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and the shipper was contacted for an amended shipper's declaration .

At 0805 ET, XPO logistics terminal XDY called to report a 1 gallon release of UN1903, Sani-T-10 Plus due to a forklift puncture from the previous terminal, impacting the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched contractors for cleanup and containment.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of product released to a 4' x 8' area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area. The damaged jug, impacted cardboard, and all cleanup debris were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 12/01/2022 at 0815, personnel in the CSXT Russell Yard discovered UTLX 67206, a loaded tank car of Xylenols liquid, emitting a strong odor from the car. The car was isolated, and the shipper, National Response Center, and Kentucky EOC were notified. (CHEMTREC Report # 2022-1201-00083). Quick Response, a CSXT approved hazardous material contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the bottom outlet valve flange inadequately secured to affect a proper seal between the valve and the bottom of the tank car resulting in a release of hazardous materials. The issue was identified, and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative, Mr. Randy Shilling, 832-783-6428. Containment was positioned under the leaking valve and attempts were made to secure the tank in accordance with 49 CFR 173.31, all released material was cleaned from the exterior of the car, and the car was placed on hazmat hold. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 not required. Cause Code:535 NARRI:60
column169: (NAR Code: 535 5 What Failed: Bottom Outlet Valve Where Failed: Connection between valve and tank car Why Failed: Mounting flange bolts/nuts less than tool tight)

column168: On December 8, 2022, at 1051 ET, XPO Logistics (UMV terminal) contacted ERTS regarding a UN3265, Corrosive, Liquid, Acidic, Organic, N.O.S., 8, PG II "Spectrus NX1100" release that occurred at 1015 ET. It was advised that up to 3 ounces of product released to the dock from a 5-gallon plastic pail due to puncture by a pallet nail. It was advised that the release was cleaned prior to ERTS being contacted and that the container and cleanup debris were placed into a steel drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to correctly containerize the release.  Contractors arrived onsite and advised terminal personnel had placed the waste into a metal drum. Crew collected the damaged jug and all cleanup debris from the metal drum and properly containerized the material into a 35-gallon poly drum. The metal drum was decontaminated for future use. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On December 8, 2022, at 1515 ET, XPO Logistics Terminal UFN experienced release of UN1824 “Car Brite Hot Stuff Concentrated Heavy Duty Degreaser” from a 5-gallon poly pail. The release impacted the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. No soils, drains, or waterways were reported to have been impacted by this release. ERTS dispatched Patriot Environmental Services to conduct all on site cleanup activities. On December 8, 2022, at 1651 EST, Patriot personnel arrived on site and advised terminal personnel had placed the waste into a 30-gallon metal drum. Crew collected the damaged jug and all cleanup debris from the metal drum and properly containerized the material into a 55-gallon poly drum. The metal drum was cleaned and sanitized for future use. All waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 1206 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal USU. It was reported that approximately 1 cup of UN1823,8,II Caustic Soda was released from a 50-pound paper bag due to unknown reasons. The release impacted the concrete dock floor. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment and cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-pound of product released to the dock floor from two damaged bags due to a puncture. The damaged bags and released product were collected and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Hazardous Materials Manager Tom Robinson found this car doing inspections in the Livonia Yard with the air valve plug less than tool tight and the valve handle in the open position. Mgr. Robinson detected vapors coming from the open valve and closed it. The plug was properly tightened, and no further remediation was necessary. The handle needed to be removed from the valve to close the valve completely. Mgr. Robinson told the shipper to get a movement approval because the handle was removed from the valve stem and the car needed to be sent to certified shop for a proper repair. The shipper got an OTMA-3 and the car was released.

XPO Terminal XDM called in to report a 2-ounce spill of UN3266 "Super Kleen" from a 5-gallon plastic drum due to a faulty cap and impacting only the top of the plastic drum itself. ERTS dispatched contractors for cleanup and containment. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-ounces of product released to the lid in a 3" x 3" area from two damaged pails due to damaged bungs as a result of improper loading. The damaged pails were collected and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 1048 ET, XPO Terminal LBL contacted ERTS to report a spill that occurred inside of a trailer and spilled out onto the ground beneath it in Port Allen, LA. The spill consisted of an unknown product which released from a 55 gallon poly drum, due to an adjacent pallet that punctured the drum while offloading the drums from the trailer. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately all 55-gallons of UN3098 Hyperflex (AFCO 4365) released from a 55-gallon poly drum to the trailer floor and asphalt parking lot in a 10' x 10' area due to a puncture. The damaged drum was containerized into an 85-gallon poly overpack. Impacted pallets were cut up and placed into two 55-gallon poly drums. Water and sodium bicarb were then utilized to neutralize the impacted areas. All spent absorbents were containerized into four 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: At 0934 ET, XPO terminal NMA reported a spill that was found in a trailer and has moved onto the dock in Byron, GA. The spill consisted of a 330-gallon plastic tote containing Spectrum RX 9800, which was found leaking inside the trailer due to what looks like a forklift blade puncture prior to arrival, causing approximately a total of 5 gallons to release inside the trailer and on the dock. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 20-gallons of product released to the trailer, dock, and concrete lot below in a combined area of 20' x 20' due to a forklift puncture. The material was transferred into a new tote. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas. The damaged tote and all cleanup debris were containerized into two 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 12/08/2022 at approximately 0900, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 294822 at the hub facility in Anchorage, reporting an undeclared paint spill.  The shipment consisted of plastic drum that was overpacked into a fiberboard box.  The shipment was discovered leaking.  Further research revealed that the plastic drum was cracked which resulted in the leak. the cause of the damage is unknown.  The shipment marked or labeled as required by IATA Regulations.  The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column168: A Memphis spill agent was called to the dangerous goods building for a leaking package it was a fiberboard box containing a class 3.  The bottom of the box was covered in what appeared to be gray paint. Inside of the fiberboard box there were two 5L paint cans and they both had positive closure rings and were in plastic bags. There was also bubble wrap for dunnage. One of the cans was dented on top causing the lid to come off allowing a release of contents inside of the box. The contents were placed into a steel salvage package and will be returned to the shipper after a new declaration has been obtained.

A Memphis spill agent was called for a package that was discovered in a drive lane.  The agent observed that the package had been crush and the outer fiberboard box was wet. There were four plastic tubes containing glass bottles inside and one bottle had been broken. The bottles were separated by fiberboard dividers and surrounded by Styrofoam peanuts. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and a new shippers declaration will be obtained before movement.
A 158 forklift operator damaged a 5 gallon pail of Isopropanol (UN1993).  The spill was cleaned with absorbent and the damaged pail was placed into a recovery pail.

column168: On December 9, 2022, one (1) 55-gallon drum of furfuryl alcohol (UN2874) was punctured by a forklift and released approximately one (1) quart of product to the dock floor. R+L personnel retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from Hull's Environmental (HE) to complete the necessary corrective actions. RLC personnel deployed granular absorbents to the spill and overpacked the damaged drum in one (1) 95-gallon overpack for disposal prior to HE's arrival. HE personnel arrived on site and deployed more granular absorbents and worked them in with hand tools. The crew then containerized all UN2874-impacted material in the same 95-gallon overpack for disposal in RLC's facility waste stream.

column168: The east exception slide called the spill office at our Memphis Hub location regarding a baggage cart in their area.  The cart contained a wet Class 3 box. The cart contained multiple dangerous goods pieces but only one was leaking. The box had noticeable wet spots on the outer package. No other packages got leaked on. There were 4 plastic bottles within a fibreboard box. There was a center divide in the box but no dunnage.  2 of teh plastic bottles had loose caps that allowed a small amount to leak out. The caps were tightened and all the contents were contained into a Steel Salvage Package. Shipment is domestic and the shipper has been contacted. Shipper will provide an amended shipper's declaration so that the shipment may continue transit.

column168: A Memphis spill agent was called to the dangerous goods building for a leaking package. While investigating the package it was discovered that one of the three paint cans had released its contents inside of the fiberboard box. The cans all had positive closure rings and were separated by dividers. The can that released had a bent chime at the top. All contents were placed into a steel salvage package and the shipper was contacted for an amended declaration for movement.

At 0959 ET, XPO Logistics terminal NMF contacted ERTS to report a spill in Hialeah, FL. XPO advised that when a driver attempted to move a pallet containing a 15 gallon poly drum of Ecolab bleach he punctured the bottom of the drum causing a 5-gallon release. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 15-gallons of product released to the trailer floor in a 5' x 3' area due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were worked into the impacted area and collected. The damaged drum, broken pallet, and spent absorbents were then placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

During sort operations at the IND hub a package was found with discoloring on the bottom of the fiberboard box. The box contained four glass bottles each containing four liters and one of the bottles broke. The bottles were packaged with egg crates on top and bottom. The contents were placed into a steel salvage package and will be returned to the shipper after a new declaration has been obtained.

column168: At 2351 ET, XPO notified ERTS of a cargo release at terminal NOF. It was reported that approximately 15 gallons of an unknown UN1590, 6.1, III was released from a 55-gallon plastic drum due to the drum being punctured by a forklift blade. The release impacted the concrete dock floor. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 25-gallons of Bare Metal Stripper released to an 18' x 21' area of the dock floor due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted area and containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The damaged drum was containerized into an 85-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Terminal XGR contacted ERTS to report a spill of approximately 20-pounds of UN3349 'Force 6.5G Insecticide" that was released from two 40-pound paper bag during transit due to being improperly loaded into the trailer. The caller stated that the release impacted the trailer floor. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 30-pounds of product released to a 5' x 5' area of the trailer floor due to improper loading. The damaged bags and all released product were collected and containerized into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

At 1039 EST - ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics domicile terminal NOF regarding a release of UN1133 Everstrong ES 700 from a 5-gallon metal pail. The spill location occurred over the road at 2717 Pemberton Dr. in Apopka, FL. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of product released to a 1' x 1' area of the trailer floor and asphalt lot below due to a puncture. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected along with the damaged pail, and all cleanup debris into a 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was removed from site for future disposal.

column168: At 0850 AM ET, XPO Terminal NNA reported a spill that occurred inside of a trailer and on the dock in Nashville, TN. The spill consisted of (1) 55 gallon poly drum of Prep Pre-Soak, which was punctured by a loose nail on the pallet it was loaded onto, and the nail caused a puncture at the bottom of the drum which caused a spill of approximately 1 gallon. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 5-gallons of product released to a 6' x 2' area of the trailer floor, 2' x 2' area of the dock and 4' x 3' area of the lot due to puncture by a pallet nail. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon poly drum to be shipped on. Impacted absorbents and cleanup debris was containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

It was advised that up to 55 gallons of product released to the trailer floor and lot from at least (1) 55-gallon steel drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup and containment of the material. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately all 55-gallons of product released to an 8' x 10' area of the trailer floor and the asphalt lot below due to a puncture. The damaged drum was placed into a 95-gallon metal drum. Absorbents were then worked into the impacted areas and collected. The impacted absorbents, contaminated pallet, and all other cleanup debris were containerized into six 55-gallon metal drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY AN UNLOADER. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG EMPLOYEE EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HER SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 1 MINUTE A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL 2" LONG CRACK ON THE BOTTON OF A PLASTIC 5-GAL PAIL, CAUSING APPROX. 10 OUNCES OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE BOTTOM OF THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: Driver was travelling in incliment, rainy, weather when he lost control of tractor trailer. The driver tried to correct the skid but lost all controll. The truck stayed upright but the trailer rolled onto its passenger side and skidded on the highway for roughly 100 yds. This skid caused all compartments on the trailer to rupture due to friction with the roadway. The ruptures allowed roughly 7800 of the the total 8000 gallons to spill onto the roadway and into the ditch on the side of the roadway.  9-11 was promptly called and services arrived at the scene within minutes.  EMT's checked the driver.  TX State Trooper performed the accident investigation.  TX Dot put out cones for lane closures and dumped sand into the ditch to keep materiels from running.
column169: Safety meetings will be conducted, stressing the importance of safe driving in incliment weather situations. The driver was couseled on this particular incident; stressing ways to possibly prevent incidents in the furture.

column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column168: AT THE UPS FACILITY IN LOUISVILLE, KY, A FULLY DECLARED LITHIUM BATTERY PACKAGE FROM HONG KONG TO USA WAS FOUND TO BE WARM TO THE TOUCH WITH A BURNT SMELL. RESPONDER FURTHER INSPECTED TO DISCOVER A SMALL AREA OF BLACK CHARRING VISIBLE ON ONE SURFACE OF THE OUTER BOX. INSPECTION OF INNER CONTENTS FOUND EVIDENCE OF A THERMAL EVENT HAVING OCCURRED. SOME OF THE BATTERIES WERE CHARRED AND CORRODED WITH FURTHER BLACK CHARRING ON THE INNER FLAPS OF THE BOX. THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY FIFTY INDIVIDUALLY LITHIUM BATTERIES IN CLAMSHELL TYPE PACKAGING WITH THE THERMAL EVENT APPEARING TO BE CONFINED TO A SMALL NUMBER OF THE BATTERIES. PRIOR TO DISCOVERY THE PACKAGE HAD PREVIOUSLY FLOWN ON UPS FLIGHTS FROM HKG TO ANC, ANC TO DISCOVERY AT SDF. THE LITHIUM BATTERY INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE NRC UNDER NRC#1355620 AS REQUIRED PER 49CFR 171.15.

column168: On December 19, 2022, one (1) 330-gallon tote of UN3265 was punctured during trasnit and released approximately thirty (30) gallons of product to the trailer floor and other pallets. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services LC who dispatched a crew GeoTek Engineering & Testing Services, Inc. (GETS) to remediate the impacted surface. GETS personnel utilized granular absorbents and scheduled to return at a later date.   On December 20, 2022, GETS personnel returned to the site. The crew used a forklift to remove the remaining contents from the damaged tote into a new 330-gallon tote. Personnel then deployed more absorbents and worked them n using hand tools. All undamaged cargo was repalletized and all UN3265-impacted material was containerized in the damaged 330-gallon tote for transport and disposal.

On December 21, 2022, one (1) 330-gallon tote experienced a loose cap and released approximately less than one (<1) gallon of UN3266 to the trailer floor and tote. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC, who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to perform the necessary corrective actions. FCE personnel re-secured the cap and utilized absorbent pads to remove the product from the floor. All UN3266-impacted material was containerized in one (1) poly-bag for disposal by FCE.

SequenceEvent: The package was a drum with a tension ring seal. the ring was locked closed with a zip tie. The package was unload off the trailer with no issue. Then as the package was being lifted and placed on a tugger cart, it was dropped on it's side. The package then leaked liquid. I would guess that the inner bag of the package must have already leaked out into the general cylinder prior to it being dropped by the package handler. DescribePack: The seal obviously was not working properly, because it should have prevented liquid from leaking out. also there was insufficient package material. The drum itself was only about 35% full, and then the just put one little thing of bubble wrap in it. They did not fill all the air space within the container to make it more damage resistant. There was also two separate sets of OP-900 Hazmat Documents on the package, making it difficult to determine what the actual content were. The two sets of documents had different track ids and different UN numbers. Both track ids were picked up from the same shipper on the same day. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Once the spill was brought to my attention, the drum had already been turned back upright and was no longer leaking. I put on ppe and moved the leaking package and other affected packages away from the site. Then I covered all the leaked liquid with chemical neutralizer. Then I called the hazmat hotline. They sent a vendor out here to finish clean up. The vendor cleaned up the neutralizer from the spill area, as well as treated the packages that the chemical spilled on. They removed the leaking drum from our building in a larger drum. The other affected packages that were treated by the vendor were to large to be returned to the shipper, so those were scrapped.

column168: On December 01, 2022 at 11:00 ET, Dolphin Line Inc. notified ERTS of a cargo release at 8301 MO-108, Arbyrd, MO. It was reported that an unknown amount of Counter20G was released from 40-lb Lock-N'-Load containers due to unknown damage during transit. The release impacted the inside of trailer #30176. No storm drains or waterways are reported to be impacted by the release.  ERTS dispatched E3 to perform the cleanup. At 1435 EST, E3 arrived on site and located the impacted container. E3 estimates about 0.25 lbs were released but the damaged box was on the bottom of the load, so E3 began unloading the boxes.  Before departing the site at 1610 EST, E3 containerized the 40 lb leaking container into a 1-55 gallon drum to be transported off-site. Waste will be staged at the E3 shop located at: 816 Nesbit Rd, Nesbit, MS 38651 until proper disposal.

column168: On 12/11/22 Schneider National contacted ERTS on behalf of Schneider Bulk to report that one of their tankers was at a Quala Wash and sunk into the pavement causing it to tip over and lean onto the tank next to it. The tanker was holding UN2789 Acetic Acid and it was unknown where the leak was coming from, but it was likely from the dome lid or crash box. On 12/11/22, at 2030 ET, Cleaning Guys (CG) arrived on site and assessed the impact areas.  The tanker was rolled on its side but at the time, it didn’t look like there was an active leak. CG estimated 3500 gallons of product spilled on the lot in a 12ft by 20ft yard area. There were several potholes in the lot where product as well as rainwater was pooling.  Since the tanker was surrounded by released product, CG could not access the tanker. CG had their skid steer en route along with the rest of the crew to scrape up the impacted parking lot, which is a soil gravel mix instead of concrete, and pile it to the side on poly sheets until they can get roll-off boxes on site.  CG was bringing a Betz Valve to assist in transferring the tanker’s remaining contents into another tanker.  A vacuum truck was also required and is en route.  The vacuum truck will be used to remove the collected product and water from the parking lot.  Then the soil will be scraped.  The liquid-collected waste will be placed into a frac tank on site until disposal can be coordinated.  The Schneider dispatched wrecking company could not perform the uprighting of the trailer.  CG dispatched Beards Towing.  CG pH tested the standing water, and it came out to a 4 so the material is safe for their frac tank.  At 0000 ET, the vacuum truck arrived, and the pumping began.  At 0205 ET, the wreckers were on site.  The tanker was uprighted at 0242 ET.  The crew began to transfer the remaining product from the damaged tanker.  At 0500 ET, CG completed the transfer.  CG placed a berm around the damaged trailer to prevent any leaking.  CG placed the impacted gravel piled on a poly sheet and will order roll-off boxes to containerize. The relief tanker departed the site.  At this point, it is estimated that approximately 8000 gallons of impacted water and 30 yards of impacted soil will be disposed of.  The site was secured for the crew to return for the remaining work.   On 12/12/22 at 1235 ET, CG returned to the site to pH spot sample the puddles to determine if any water needs to be pumped and take a water sample from the creek/pond to determine if there is any impact there.  All readings were neutral. The pond is approximately 1500ft from the spill site. ERTS reached out to Schneider and determined the original amount in the tanker was 5389 gallons.  At 1302 ET, TCEQ Will Daughtrey, called and was updated on the progress.  He also stated the TCEQ will only require confirmation pH sampling taken to a lab to show the areas in question being below the background areas.  Mr. Daughtrey visited the site and assessed the site in person.  There

column168: SequenceEvent: I was informed by a tugger that a package on the unload j-loop, just off of the conveyor belt was dripping something. The box was immediately placed in a hazmat lined bin and taken to the hazmat cage hood fan/vent. A very small amount was on the floor, and was cleaned up with absorbent pads, which were placed in the bin as well. Once in the hood vent the package began emitting smoke. The cage was isolated and I called the FedEx spill response service, who came in approximately four hours later and completely cleaned the hazmat cage area and placed the broken product and box, bag and pads in a 55 gallon hazmat bin. Their protective equipment was all placed in a separate 55 gallon hazmat bin and they were sealed. I believe the company was EnviroCare. DescribePack: The bottle was broken, but other than that I do not know how. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The small amount which spilled was immediately absorbed with pads and placed in bin. The FedEx spill response service performed the cleaning of the hazmat cage area and sealed the product and all related items in drums.

column168: SequenceEvent: Heavy snow storm caused trailers to be late for unloading. This lead to trailers being exposed to sub-zero Farenheit temperatures longer than usual for shipment of packages. In turn, this lead to the package freezing and cracking, ultimately spilling a small amount of the paint from the crack at the bottom of the drum. Cleaned up in-house with rubber gloves, paper towels, and HAZMAT approved blue bag to contain all HAZMAT and PPE after clean up. DescribePack: The bottom of the drum is bulging outward and cracked. Could not determine exact size of crack due to red pain seeping through crack. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The drum was placed in a HAZMAT approved blue bag, and further placed in a yellow, Damage HAZMAT transfer drum.

SequenceEvent: At some point the package began leaking while driver was transporting package on route. It is unknown what caused the damage. Driver retrieved a salvage drum (unknown source) to contain spill. The salvage drum had the correct Corrosive 8 labeling on it to match the contents. Action taken: intake by QA and placed salvage drum in Hazardous Materials processing area/cage. QA inspected and processed damage report following day (12/21/2022). DescribePack: The only damage observed was leakage. All leakage seems to have occurred in the top-most area of package. Closures were open due to leakage. There were no vents or seals on inner packaging. Closures on bottom of package were still intact. DurationRel: 4 and MitigateEffect: Driver was able to place package in a bag and salvage drum.

SequenceEvent: Package was brought to QA due to noticeable damage to the outside of the packaging. The box was then secured & placed in a secure area to await processing. DescribePack: Upon further inspection it was discovered to have been caused by one of the four internal containers having a crack on the bottom of the bottle resulting in leak & damage to another package. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Package was stationed in a well ventilated area to await further processing & placed into a plastic lined bucket to contain any more leaking liquid.

SequenceEvent: Plastic pail was brought over to QA during sort. DescribePack: After further inspection the lid of the pail was wet due to the cap being loose. DurationRel: 0 and MitigateEffect: We were able to place the plastic pail in a lined tote to prevent further spillage.

column168: On December 12, 2022, GrayMar Environmental Services was dispatched to the site. column168: On December 15, 2022, Moran Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 4ft-by-3ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that seven (7) gallon of material was released. Moran Environmental personnel  neutralized  the  impacted  area  and  used  granular  absorbents  to  collect  the  material.  The spent absorbents, debris, and Personal Protective Equipment (PPE) were placed into two (2) 55-gallon poly drum. The generated waste containers were transported offsite by Moran Environmental personnel to process for disposal.
column198: EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND TRAINING SOLUTIONS, INCORPORATED

column168: On December 17, 2022, Enviroserve was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel investigated and located one (1) leaking 25-liter jerrican inside a crate that released three (3) ounces of material. Enviroserve personnel determined that the jerrican had a bad seal that resulted in the material being released. The contractor neutralized the impacted area and undamaged jerricans in the crate. Two jerricans was placed into two (2) 55-gallon poly drum and the other twelve (12) undamaged containers were placed into three (3) 55-gallon poly drums. One additional 55-gallon poly drum was generated containing the contractor’s personal protective equipment (PPE). Two (2) super sacks were generated containing the non-impacted crate and Styrofoam. The three (3) 55-gallons poly drums will be sent on to its destination. The generated waste containers were transported offsite by Enviroserve personnel to process for disposal.

Resolute Environmental & Response Services stated that  five (5) totes were damaged when the driver  had a hard stop. The empty totes were left at the contractor’s shop to be processed for disposal. The generated waste containers were transported offsite by Resolute Environmental & Response Services personnel to process for disposal.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column62: Defective Component or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: Car was reported leaking by conductor during inspection.  Steady drips coming out from around the bottom outlet cap and falling on the ties.  We checked the valve and verified it was closed and tried to tighten the cap.  We were unalbe to stop the leak.  The cap was removed and we found the valve was not holding and a steady stream of product was coming out.  We replaced the gasket in the cap and tightened the cap with a 36" wrench.  Leak was stopped.  We verified leak free for 30 minutes and then released car to be delivered.  Shipper was contacted to request OTMA and consignee was contacted to not release car once it was made empty. without an OTMA.

column168: On 12/07/2022 at approximately 0900, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 5269340 at the station location in Farmington, reporting an undeclared resin spill. The shipment was a fiberboard box, containing a can labeled resin as well as other nonhazardous items. The package emitted an odor during the loading process. Further research revealed that the resin labeled container leaked inside of the box. The package was not labeled in accordance with IATA Regulations. The shipment is being held, pending an FAA investigation.

column168: On 12/08/2022 Veolia employees were loading drums into a trailer at the Veolia, Schenecady, NY facility when an employee noticed that a 55-gallon plastic drum was slightly leaking. It is assumed that another employee mistakenly punctured a 55 gallon plastic drum when it was being loaded onto the trailer the day before. The drum was placed immediately on its side to prevent it from leaking further and then was overpacked into an 851A2 salvage drum to continue transportation to the ultimate disposal facility.     The drum leaked about 1/2 gallon of class 9 material with waste chromium solution. The liquid was cleaned up with spill pads and absorbent and the drum was overpacked into an appropriate 85 gallon salvage drum along with the clean up materials. The duration of release is anticipated to be about 24 hours but due to the small hole, only about 1/2 a gallon leaked. The drum was still substantially full when the leak was discovered.   On 12/08/2022 the Veolia safety manager was notified and an investigation was performed. The results of the investigation revealed that a newer employee was assisting another employee with the shipment. The trailer was being filled with containers and the employee was not immediately aware that they had poked a hole in the drum until notified the following day by Veolia EHS.
column169: Human error was identified as the cause of the incident. The two employees who loaded the trailer were notified of the leak and reminded to be more careful when loading drums with a drum cart.

column168: RESPONDER RECEIVED A CALL FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE UNLOAD WALL. UPON ARRIVAL, RESPONDER IDENTIFIED SAID LEAKING PACKAGE. PLACED PACKAGE IN SPILL TRAY. TRANSPORTED PACKAGE TO DMP AREA FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

The Veolia driver stopped to refuel at a truck stop. As he was refueling, he took the time to do a quick walk-around inspection. He found a small leak at the end of the trailer. He opened up the end of the trailer and found that the lid of a tote had popped off. This may have been caused by a build up of pressure in the tote during transportation. He put on some PPE and cleaned up the spill. Less than 1 quart of material had spilled. He then notified his supervisor of the spill.
column169: The shipper has been asked to make sure let the solution settle out prior to closing the container and releasing it for transportation in the future.

column168: DURING PACKAGE X-RAY AT THE CHEK LAP KOK INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT, LITHIUM ION BATTERIES WERE FOUND INSIDE A PADDED UPS PAK. THE PAK WAS OPENED FOR INSPECTION WHICH CONFIRMED FOUR VAPCELL INR26650 5500 MAH LITHIUM ION BATTERIES THAT WERE PACKAGED INSIDE AN ADDITIONAL USPS PADDED MAILER. THE FOUR LITHIUM BATTERIES WERE SECURED INSIDE USPS PADDED MAILER IN TWO HARD PLASTIC-TYPE CLEAR CONTAINERS. THERE ARE NO DANGEROUS GOODS MARKS OR LABELS ON THE OUTER PACKAGING TO INDICATE DANGEROUS GOODS WERE BEING SHIPPED. THE CUSTOMS INVOICE DESCRIBES PACKAGE CONTENTS AS 4 X 26650 ALUMINUM TUBES. THERE IS AN ITEM ORDER DOCUMENT THAT WAS FOUND DURING INSPECTION INSIDE THE PAK WITH A DESCRIPTION OF VAPCELL INR26650 5500 MAH RECHARGEABLE LITHIUM ION BATTERY 4 X 4.

column168: On 12/31/2022 at 1342 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Florence Yard (Florence, SC) discovered UTLX211155, a loaded tank car of Ethyl Acrylate, Stabilized leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Sasol was notified. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found the vapor line open and the secondary closure plug less than tool tight. The issue was identified, and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Sasol Scott Guidry 337-499-1488. HEPACO closed the vapor line and tightened the secondary closure plug tool tight. The car was released back into transportation without delays.
column169: NAR code: 136 vapor line valve plug less than tool tight

column168: At 0858 ET, XPO Logistics terminal XEM called to report a 2.5-gallon release of UN3265 Spectrus NX1106 due to a pinhole puncture in a poly drum. The containers were refused by the customer due to the pinhole punctures and had been sitting in the OS&D bay since December 21th 2022. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct containment.  Contractors arrived onsite and advised the three jugs had pinhole punctures, however there was no release at the time of the contractor’s response. Crew confirmed there was no product on the dock or pallet to clean. The damaged jugs were containerized into an 80-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: Freight handlers need to pay attention to freight staged on the dock to help prevent these types of unintentional releases from occurring.

column168: Facility was receiving a load of sodium bisulfite 40% into its SBS tank (Tank 19).  During the receipt, the tank ruptured releasing the entire contents into our tank farm containment dike and splashing over to the covered truck loading bays.   A vent trap exterior to the storage tank that scrubs the tank's head space as it is filled was frozen due to the extreme low temperatures in the days before the release.  The vent trap is a small storage tank containing water where the working losses of the storage tank are sparged through the water before being released to atmosphere. Two emergency response contractors were called but facility employees pumped the containment before the emergency response contractors could arrive. No injuries. Release was not reportable to government agencies as the chemical did not release “into the environment”.
column169: New procedures will be developed to ensure the liquid in the vent trap does not freeze prior to starting a tank fill once a new tank is ordered and installed.

column168: On December 21, 2022, SET Environmental arrived onsite and observed five (5) gallons of Sodium Bisulfite Solution 40% had been released impacting a 2ft-by-20ft area of trailer floor and a 3ft-by-10ft area of concrete in the terminal parking lot. SET Environmental personnel determined that the poly totes had been overfilled and as a result of cold weather the material expanded and leaked out of the top of the totes. One tote was damaged with a pinhole puncture and the contents of the tote was transferred to a new tote. The other non-damaged tote had a small amount transferred to a new tote to relieve pressure. SET Environmental personnel used soda ash to neutralize the impacted areas and to the leaking totes and then deployed oil dry to impacted areas. The spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum and the damaged tote was broken down and placed into one (1) 55-gallon poly drum. All waste and transferred totes were left onsite.

column168: On 12/27/2022 at 2208hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Fairburn GA Terminal discovered TCNU495504, a loaded container of 1 T/L FREIGHT ALL KINDS, (FAK) DATA COMUNICATION DEVICES, released less than 1 pint of a burgundy fluid and was steaming from a vent on top of the trailer with minimal amount onto asphalt pavement.  The container lading was both NonHaz and HazMat. The container was isolated and the local Fire Dept was notified, report# To Be Provided.  The shipper, ZIM AMERICAN INTEGRATED SHIPNG representative was notified by CSX Intermodal Customer Service; case#00590974. CSX emergency response contractor, HULLS Environmental, was dispatched to the scene; secured the contaminated areas, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the release site.  The original freight trailer was released to the rail shipper. The issue was identified as inadequate packaging, and improper loading method, to prevent lading self-ignition.  Issue also identified as non-compliant lading description as nonhaz Freight All Kinds, when inner labels showed lading as UN3480, Lithium Ion Batteries, Class 9.  Corrective actions were communicated to the shipper along with request to provide compliant, or exemption, documentation for the lading description.

column168: On December 29, 2022, Logiflex notified ERTS of a 50-plus gallon release of UN 2735 Corrgaurd from a 330-gallon tote inside a trailer and in the yard of a Castrol facility.  Enviroserve arrived on site and entered the trailer but could not confirm why totes were leaking.  The tops were sunken in, but no product was visible.  The crew used a forklift to unload the trailer and stated that the tote suspect to leaking was at the front of the trailer. Enviroserve was on the last tote and stated the tote was leaking due to a nail puncture on the bottom of the tote.  It was estimated 30 gallons impacted a 47ft by 8 ft area of the trailer and approximately one gallon spilled outside of the trailer and impacted a 5ft by 2ft area of the ashpalt of the parking lot. Enviroserve shredded the damaged tote and placed it into a 55-gallon poly waste drum.  The trailer floor was worked in and applying absorbents and sweeping them into poly drums. All undamaged totes were then loaded onto the trailer and would be returned to the shipper.  (5) poly drums were generated and staged at the terminal until profiled then disposed of properly.

On December 30, 2022 at 0430 ET, an XPO Logistics terminal NTR tractor trailer was traveling down I-40 when the unit was involved in a roll over accident occurring at mile marker 418 eastbound. As a result, the unit experienced an over the road cargo release from multiple 5-gallon and 1-gallon containers of non-regulated On an' On, non-regulated  Tribase, non-regulated Xcelente, non-regulated Clean by 4D, UN1903 Sani-T Plus, & UN1750 RJ8 Tile & Grout Rejuvenator. Additional products Honda Dual Pump Fluid II & Glass Cleaner Non-Ammoniated Formula were damaged but not releasing. ERTS dispatched contractors to the scene to help conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 50-gallons in total of the above products released to the asphalt lot in a 15' x 5' area and the soil shoulder in a 2' x 2' area due to an over the road roll over accident. Contractors advised the majority of the release was from four damaged 5-gallon containers of non-regulated On an' On which were completely empty of all contents. Crew completed a soil scrape to collect all impacted soil. Absorbents were worked into the impacted trailer floor and asphalt roadway and collected along with the soil into a 55-gallon metal drum. All damaged and impacted product were collected and containerized by product into 13 waste drums. The waste was transported to XPO's terminal located in Blountville, TN for personnel to manage. Sample analysis is currently pending for the soil scrape completed and once received, the incident will be closed.

The PVS Transportation terminal team arrives to the customer site and cleaned up the release.

column168: On December 24, 2022, at approximately 20:53 local time (01:53 UTC), N558JB, an Airbus A320 operating as scheduled Flight 662 from Bridgetown, Barbados (BGI) to New York, NY (JFK) experienced a Customer-initiated emergency evacuation due to a Lithium Ion Battery Thermal Runaway.  While pulling into the gate, a battery charger belonging to the Customer seated in seat 8D appeared to be smoking.  Once parked at the gate the flight crew began the emergency evacuation checklist, and made the "Cabin Crew at Stations" call, but did not give the "EASY VICTOR" command (the command to begin an evacuation).  The Captain went back into the cabin and used a halon fire extinguisher and cold water to cool the unit down.  Aircraft Rescue and Firefighting (ARFF) had been contacted and were on the jet bridge when the main boarding door was opened.  Before the jet bridge was attached, Customers opened the over-wing emergency exit doors, apparently without instructions from the crew.  Both the right and left doors were opened resulting in deployments of both over-wing slides.  Approximately 63 Customers exited the aircraft via the slides with the remainder exiting the aircraft through the main boarding door and Jet Bridge.  During an initial review of closed-circuit television footage from the gate area, it was noted that a large number of customers climbed out of the over-wing doors and went down the slides with large roller board or similar luggage in hand.  There were no serious injuries reported among the 128 customers and 6 crewmembers.  Three customers reportedly were evaluated by emergency medical personnel for smoke inhalation and two others for elbow pain.  All five were cleared without further treatment.  There was no significant damage reported to the aircraft.  Tech Ops evaluated the aircraft and removed it from service.
column169: WE will review the procedures for incidents like this to clarify the chain of custody for the device which caused the issue.

column168: A passengers vape device caught fire in his bag under his seat and started to bum with his personal belongings. Passengers in the aft cabin yelled fire and I looked up and could see smoke in the aft cabin. Flight Attendant was working the cart during a service with another Flight Attendant. We pushed the cart immediately into the first class galley and one Flight Attendant grabbed the PBE and another Flight Attendant grabbed the fire extinguisher from the stowage spot. Flight Attendant just grabbed the first extinguisher they found since they didn't know at this time what kind of fire we were dealing with and didn't want to run to the back with nothing and then have to go back for an extinguisher thus possibly wasting valuable time. We arrived to the aft cabin and by this time another passenger who happened to be a Federal Air Marshall had already grabbed the device and placed it in the mid cabin Iavatory sink. We made sure the fire was out by continuing to run water on it while we went through the passengers bag to ensure that it was also no longer a threat. The passenger was totally compliant and admitted it was his device and offered any assistance we needed. After the fire was out we calmed down a few concerned passengers and Flight Attendant #4 who was a bit shaken and then resumed our duties. No one was hurt and we landed safely in L.A. FA#2 was in the aft Iav and was not involved directly and FA#1 was the communicator with the flight deck.
